natural problem: Compute $\arctan \left( -\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \right).$  Express your answer in radians.

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x :: real
assumes h0 : "x = - 1 / sqrt 3"
shows  "arctan x = - pi / 6"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Compute $\arctan \left( -\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \right).$  Express your answer in radians. The final Answer is -\frac{\pi}{6}
 ### Proof
 Since $\tan \left( -\frac{\pi}{6} \right) = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}},$ $\arctan \left( -\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \right) = \boxed{-\frac{\pi}{6}}.$
 *)

theorem
fixes x :: real
assumes h0 : "x = - 1 / sqrt 3"
shows  "arctan x = - pi / 6"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
a_0.informal problem: Find the arctangent of $x$ when $x = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}$. The final answer is $-\frac{\pi}{6}$.
